A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama ’ s Re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
But the Brennan Center believes the latter to be a myth, affirming that electoral fraud in the US is less common than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for the conduct of state elections.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of US governments have passed new laws that make the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to provide photo identification and proof of U.S. citizenship.
Furthermore, these laws also shorten the timescales for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day and deny citizens the right to vote for which there is a judicial file.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to show photo identification.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The United States Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal health card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their country.
Moreover, five million new voters do not have such a badge in 2012.
However, often more than a hundred dollars have to be paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people on low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo identification.
This goes even further.
Students who are considered voters, who increasingly vote for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting associations who vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no federal state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
For it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
Moreover, in 2011, Republican lawmakers promoted laws in eight states that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections helped to register around 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters registering by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
Moreover, Republican legislators in five other states have enacted legislation aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in Florida ’ s 2008 general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, though they make up only 13% of the state ’ s voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of those who voted in advance.
By contrast, whites, who made up 76% of voters, made up only 46% of pre-voting voters.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills were blocked by the veto of democratic governors.
The US Advocate General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have enacted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the enacted laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing outcomes in the states that will decide in 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states that passed these laws accounted for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: should the test be done or not?
The PPE test does, in fact, sometimes show faulty results, with false negative or false positive results, leading to unnecessary medical intervention.
This leads to more hesitation on the part of men who are already undecided about carrying out screening tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We asked for the opinion of two specialists.
In the studies conducted in the United States, there were a number of interference factors between the control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that in follow-up after 12 years, the probability of metastasis formation is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection was performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 or 40 if you have a direct relative who has already contracted prostate cancer.
There is also a higher risk for men of African American descent.
The most important thing is to make the right decision as soon as cancer is detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient really needs to be made aware of the extent to which his cancer is at risk, by identifying the possible options for prostate cancer to go untreated if it does not affect the quality of life in the long term, and opting in these cases for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are not treated because their cancer is not aggressive and poses no threat to their lives.
They are offered active surveillance and treatment as the disease progresses.
The criteria for deciding who should and who should not be treated are determined with increasing precision.
That is why I still recommend that the test be carried out.
But the most important thing is to talk to your doctor to determine whether it should be done or not.
In cooperation with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed an instrument that makes it possible to evaluate the advantages and disadvantages of the PPE test.
