Analysis of the Higgs ’ Boson
The announcement last summer of the probable discovery of the Higgs, Boson, caused quite a stir, and for good reason.
In fact, this boson is believed to be involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted but not yet empirically observed by the Standard Model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs "boson" predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but data is still missing to be completely safe.
Nevertheless, let us assume that it is indeed the Higgs, because there seems to be little risk of deception, and let us look at what it is all about.
In this world, there is an inevitable law that causes two objects not to exist at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and do not try too hard, as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state", whereby this "state" by and large consists of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner there are the good citizens, which are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other move the bosons, an evil gang of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing, by the way), these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we are not going to cover here, and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature are spreading and with which the Higgs "boson would be somehow related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "particle of light", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this very place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" gives rise to an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same is true for the Higgs-boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs-field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs ’ field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be furrowed by a very large rock.
Therefore, a giant particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - is required to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is helpful again to explain the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
Likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs ’ field: those who do do do have mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all this research be 'good for', asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they serve to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately examine any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are many physicists, who hope that such deviations will be found, because the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes of the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has big deficiencies, as it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general public is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is none.
By the way: in the early sixties, the pioneers of lasers in Bell ’ s laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous wave laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially seen as more of a "laboratory toy".
Imagine...
Applications can also come from all the tools that surround research.
In 1969, for example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... | Le Devoir
Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its Committee on Dying with Dignity.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the palliative care home in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The illness does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating.
Sitting at the table before a tasty lunch, he resigned to let himself be helped with the meal.
He even courageously manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is for my diarrhea to be cured, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing while standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist in the home of Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability," he says, "to take a step backwards."
According to several people working in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these regressions.
The patients, who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor, Gadbois, all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who look after them no longer overwhelm them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But I really got to know my children through the illness.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says before she accepts that a mask be put on to help her breathe.
She still expects a last visit of her son, who comes from Italy, in the next days.
In the home of Victor O. Gadbois, a group of volunteers offers personal hygiene and food intake assistance.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That is very little, considering that one day we will all die.
This is where life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the home ’ s doctors.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given an oral hygiene treatment with brandy or pepsi.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Yesterday evening we served Mr X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
There is no day like the other in the home of Victor O. Gadbois.
Next to an old man of 93 who enjoys the last family reunion in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows while being toasted to his honour, a young man of 36, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel, alarmed.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor ’ Gadbois Home come from their homes, and 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when they reach the end of their lives, either at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor ’ Gadbois Home and the Montreal Greater Palliative Care Society, are specializing more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this major deficiency in Quebec health care that causes several palliative care specialists to be concerned about passing a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec ’ s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in great pain in the emergency room for 14 days without any measures being taken to relieve her.
I fear that the only reason patients want to die is because they do not receive adequate healthcare.
And at the same time, despite the worst forecasts, several oncologists doggedly treat their patients until the last day.
Hélène Richard ’ s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she told me that she regretted that I gave up the fight.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not complying with this request after their pain was alleviated by a palliative care team.
It must be clearly stated, however, that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Greater Montreal Domestic Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of their lives, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which amounts to putting the patient to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend not to perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to fall back on this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pains are not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But this does not necessarily mean "I want you to put me to sleep", but "I want my pain to be relieved".
The realisation of this report was possible due to a journalism grant from Canadian health research institutes.
Real estate scandals on a large scale in Quebec
