With Bitcoin it is possible to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and handling fees between the parties.
Moreover, as is so often the case with these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the belief that the current monetary system, shaped by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol such as BitTorrent, which enables the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers in the network, around 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After peaking at $30 ($23) in June 2011, Bitcoin fell to $2 five months later, before recovering to about $10 today (listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits", which are used to advance in a video game, which you can win or buy (and sometimes trade back) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositories of the invoice book, auditors, monetary authorities, issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoin is present in the account book of public accounts that is distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of temporary central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay two times very fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money to cheat, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the problem receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, the reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The amount of Bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but divisible to a hundred-millionth, which leaves some room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement of computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin inserts have been stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol", assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Major players such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the blog, platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann institute in Israel analyzed the account book and showed that almost 80% of the Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega sales" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the Coinabul company, which converts Bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which are thus cheaper.
In addition, the holder maintains his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented at retailers and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You simply have to enter an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend to rethink hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point, ” he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB envisages a reassessment of the various risks that it now considers to be high if this currency succeeds.
We have left Afghanistan.
And then?
French troops have left their responsibilities in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain possession of its territory and for the Afghan people to decide their future without expecting anything from us.
We have punished Afghan farmers in particular by treating them as terrorists.
And ourselves with our 88 killed soldiers, as well as the injured and injured.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but often also farmers who refuse an armed foreign presence, as in the Soviet era.
They want to defend their centuries-old and archaic traditions, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks and Tajiks.
If tolerated, sometimes supported by the local insurgents, the latter will no longer be there when Western countries become more discreet.
The withdrawal of the French troops from the base in Nijrab, which I observed from a hill planted with almond trees and financed with French loans, was proper.
The convoys of trucks and tanks overflown by helicopters have reached Kabul without being attacked.
From the end of 2014, there will be no more Taliban influx into Kabul.
Conditions have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
At that time Kabul was empty and the country was overrun by war due to the struggles of the various insurgent groups.
Their seizure of power was then seen as a kind of liberation and return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of farmers overwhelmed by Al Qaeda, but their situation has not improved to date.
Former Mujahedin, the Afghan government, and the current Taliban have a common desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main figures of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have turned into profiteers by confiscating government land to sell as building land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, taking advantage of America ’ s massive subcontracting.
They have brought themselves into disrepute, and most of them were not themselves involved in the fighting.
As I have heard in the campaigns, people want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the country, like those who have benefited from American grants: capital flight is considerable.
Young people are fed up with war and its ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they had contact with the modern world and enjoyed its benefits.
Approximately 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, which is one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, state schools are full of girls and boys.
These young people, who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the former parties or the corruption of certain leaders, will have to be given jobs.
Everyone, including the armed parties, is obsessed with mobile phones; television, with its Turkish series representing a modern world, is watched everywhere.
An army is now in place.
Are the authorities under whose authority it will be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already trying to restore the militias in the province, which will escape the power of the central government.
Afghanistan, the country of mountains with strong local identities, should have benefited from a certain decentralization, on the example of the Western nations, but by abolishing the office of Prime Minister, which existed since the constitution of 1964, the USA wanted to make of it a centralized state with a strong presidential power.
President Karzai does not want any foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
However, his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before that.
Industries have not been rebuilt, functioning dams are not in place and important irrigation systems have not been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced apart from fruit and vegetables.
Priority will be given to private initiative.
In a country devastated by 30 years of war, state control of infrastructure would have been necessary.
The rumor was spread that Afghanistan possessed immense mineral resources.
This reinforces the impression that Western countries were only there to seize it.
Mining is not possible without energy to process the iron ore or copper ore locally, or without means of transport for export via the mountains.
The Chinese have almost left the copper mine of Mes Aynak, the international archaeologists (financed by the World Bank) have their excavations carried out on the huge Buddhist site and remain the most important employers of the province.
One day it will also be necessary to restore normal relations to Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports are largely dependent.
The withdrawal of the French combat troops was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aid: high schools for girls and boys, French university institute, French Institute, military, legal, medical and agricultural cooperation, and support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a Civil Military Action Service of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), which ceased in 2012, has carried out in dozens of mountain villages numerous community works and agricultural rehabilitation measures, and has had them carried out by a small French non-governmental organization to try to "win hearts and minds" and achieve the impossible task of compatibility of aid and offensive actions.
This work, which required a large number of local workers, has helped to suppress the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increased agricultural land.
Which souvenir will we leave behind after military expenditure of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will help to improve local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often at altitudes of more than 2000 metres.
The Embassy has received dozens of written enquiries about small agricultural projects from municipalities in the province of Kapisa.
In order for farmers to free themselves from the uprising led by foreign groups, which is what they themselves say they want, it would be necessary for them to continue to receive small, well-controlled civilian aid that affects them directly.
A Constitution with a Crowbar in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever on the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to put all its eggs in one basket.
To the surprise of everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this plenary two extra months to complete its work.
Egypt has now been relying for almost two years on a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample the law."
Its advocates assure us that one way is to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that compels the Brothers to renounce their plan to explain the text to the Egyptians, section by section.
It is also a way for the president to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
According to an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum by resorting to a hasty vote: 'Either you vote in favour of my draft or I keep the unlimited power', the latter supposedly having come to an end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Group of the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe has not complied with this request.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned their backs, believing that they were unable to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to reach the quorum, 11 persons, alternate members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that most of the articles were adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time of the prayer, since some members of the board were of the opinion that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which attracted all the attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
'Hypocrisy 'replies the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which confers an advisory role on the University, particularly with regard to the verification of conformity with Sharia law.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people invited to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
In this one can see the first signs of a theocracy. "
Liberals ’ fears are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university will be far less moderate than the current one.
"At present no concrete religious commitment is to be recognized.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, some of whom have been trained in the French system, "soothes Alexis Blouet, who is writing a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be ambiguity with respect to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, editor's note].
And in the future the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on this. "
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticised for the wide-ranging powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that they are markedly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have demanded.
The latter also share their concerns about the text, which they regard as threatening freedom.
Blasphemy is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly for the press.
Moreover, no article refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
That word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comforts and unspoilt nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons to visit Israel.
Bowing to the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God ’ s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on water, calming the storm and fishing.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the Resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries, however, are in Jerusalem.
Faithful walk here the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The trail starts at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada are the remains of the secret hiding place that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins by themselves.
All others take a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
There is a shuttle bus from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an old legend, pagan gods lived on the mountain top.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are almost 300 museums.
Not all of them can be visited with just one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel ’ s Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in caves in the Judean desert, as well as approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection includes works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Al Basha spa, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of former visitors and bathing attendants.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells the story of one of the most harrowing chapters in history.
The most moving section is the Monument to the Children, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children exterminated in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
On entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died resound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for your health
Israel's three main recreational areas are on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, bathers also swim in the Red Sea in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 ° C and the air warms up to 23 ° C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed there all year round.
This unusual sea, 417 metres below sea level, is the deepest in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salinity and therefore carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and medicinal mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and calming of strained nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is said to hold all those who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo opportunities.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theatre and conquer the Crusader fortress.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city in Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Nowadays, evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Tourist list
If you go to Israel, don ’ t worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is better not in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you can usually get by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a fast tram and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
Strictly speaking, it is an underground funicular railway.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a journey of up to 1.5 hours, including a transfer.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
Markets and shops are closed from Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, and public transport is at a standstill.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and pubs, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and food containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from a variety of mutton and beef dishes, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus, paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), and fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are many well-nourished cats, who roam comfortably and undisturbed through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like animated places and don't say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Key figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and the Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Country, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the lifting of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The big and powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While members of parliament and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Every year 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the homeland.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Service, the tests are to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
It is necessary to pass not only language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problems and protection of rights
All examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian Peoples' Friendship University, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in any city; more than 160 such centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Board.
Before the law came into force, however, civil rights activists asked the following question several times in the press: What is the point?
What are the changes brought about by the requirement to demonstrate language skills, both for Russians and for migrant workers?
Above all, according to spokesmen for the migration authority, the aim is to reduce the number of forced laborers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the Representation of the Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Viktor Zebelev.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems are encountered by migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical expertise.
Zebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will remain with dozens of his peers for months without food or documents and toil 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland you are promised the one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be confiscated and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Central Office for Labour Migration of the Tajik Migration Board, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their living in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks, and Tajiks can afford a decent primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school things.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills", they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasise the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "No Access for Unauthorized Persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
This is due to bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely forged and we are not registered, and this leads to cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajik Umed Huschkadamow told journalists.
"Don't shy away from any costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it became apparent that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some of the fake certificates that certify the language assessment have already been confiscated by staff of the Federal Migration Service.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests in this way paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that certificates cannot simply be bought.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise foreign workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal weapons market
Percentage of legal weapons in criminal offences extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten up the arms law for private gun owners.
In doing so, the authorities are reacting to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the shooting of the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma ’ s Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that the amendments to the Law on Weapons would be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by 'tightening the screws'.
An open letter has been published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various arms associations - demand that the authorities refrain from "pointless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while for the same period a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
At present, according to the authors, every possible weapon can be found in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves, ” says Baranez.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, the law enforcement officers are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen both from police armoury and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other weapons sold illegally come from military stockpiles.
In many military camps there were frequent explosions.
“There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons, ” says the former military official.
According to Baranez, arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Nowadays there are countless private armament factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore dump their weapons on the black market, for example in Moscow," reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Particularly many pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is an own, sometimes artisanal production as well as a Mafia, which organizes the smuggling ”, explains the former military member.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Analysis of Problems and State Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly accessible data on portals on the subject of weapons.
According to the investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and the legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market have arrived there through the "fault of those responsible for dealing with weapons in their work", the report says.
According to researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict zones, 14% from thefts in the production of weapons and 5% from illegal excavations.
A sales advisor from an arms shop, who does not want to be named, assures us that weapons found during illegal excavations have not been bought for a long time because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to obtain supplies in an arms depot.
A weapon, such as a TT pistol, is purchased through an ensign.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the weapon to the city and sells it there for 900 euros apiece with two magazines," he says.
“The police know everything, of course, and therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically buy checks from traders selling illegal weapons, ” the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers often find each other through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs, when someone noticed me and suggested to me to come to the station "Begovaya", where a person would wait for me, who would bring me to a certain place, where we could then negotiate the price.
The price for the weapon I learned only there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but you have to go there and make an appointment with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who lets it be known that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I currently even get some knuckles about an acquaintance I trust.
He also gives me the knuckles only because he knows that I don't whistle him.
Newcomers look for weapons in different ways.
Former military official Viktor Baranez tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on the subject.
