Almost Food- and Supermarket Workers Strike in the United States
Every fourth U.S. American teenager sits at some point behind the box office of Mc Donald's
In recent days, there have been massive protests across the US against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast-food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell further, or whether they will soon run out of steam.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organisations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of ordinary Walmart and Nearly Food-related workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of establishing trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy is hardly unionized.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, which saw sales in the US that attracted millions of customers, sometimes leading to scuffles.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their jobs and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, attacked chain branches targeting low- and middle-income people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers, hunting guns and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products in Walmart ’ s stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
As a result, many of Walmart ’ s low-paid workers buy only in their own jobs.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell goods so cheaply only because its employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or hand-held scanners.
Participants in the Black Friday protests called for wage increases and expressed anger that the contribution to company-owned health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 per month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 per hour cannot afford this increase, they said.
Researchers at California University in Berkeley have shown that if the company increased the average wage to $12 per hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That is about 1.1% more than you now donate for wages.
If Walmart applied the wage increases entirely to customers, each purchase would cost them just 46 cents more.
They would spend just $12.39 a year more than they do today.
Advocates of Walmart are pleased to note that there have been protests in only nine states, which have not caused the company any losses.
Black Friday lasted into its store from 8 p.m. on Thursday night to midnight the next day, and during that period Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company ’ s spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post that a total of “less than five ” Walmart employees were laying off work and that the protest action was merely“ another PR trick ” by the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where they targeted McDonald's and other low-priced restaurants, not Walmart branches (which are unwanted in this advanced city and therefore non-existent).
McDonald's says the company sells billions of portions and yet you are not given sick days and you are not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York legislation is $7.25 per hour.
In fast foodstuffs restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually being raised, but not too much, and on average, their employees in New York get $8.90 per hour.
No one in this expensive city earns less than this.
How it is possible to get by in New York with so little money is beyond me.
There used to be a time when almost a quarter of all American youths lived behind the counter at McDonald's after school, but the youths still lived with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald's employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they have to make do with this salary and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the forum of the Wall Street Journal, whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protest, which began Thursday morning at 6: 30 a.m. in front of McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that the cashiers and chefs of Fast Food Restaurants receive a minimum wage of US $15 per hour, more than double the current minimum wage.
They continued to call for the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
The U.S. federal law prohibits corporate management from standing in the way of this goal, warning or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate governance does not make it easy for them.
Establishing trade unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high staff turnover.
Discontented people
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The high point of the protest was a midday gathering in front of McDonald's in Times Square, where some local Democrats spoke, including City Councillor Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's say it sells billions of servings, and yet you are not given sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!"
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, Mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should work together to support the Fast Food employees so that they can receive a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!".
According to the New York Times, this was the largest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. Fast Food industry.
However, there were only a few hundred people on the ground, not all of whom are employed in the fast food industry, which employs tens of thousands in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize whole masses.
"Up to now, the brain can only be tricked moderately"
The topic of augmented reality, popular with followers of modern technology, has lately been usually perceived through the lens of special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, and in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a patent.
However, in a conversation with Shahram Izadi, head of the Interactive 3D Technology Group at Microsoft ’ s Cambridge laboratory, it became clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company ’ s scientists.
It attracts the possibility to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and to create virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is conducting.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to extend the limits of this interaction.
Until now, most of humanity has been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look forward to five to ten years and foresee the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect ’ s sensors are an advance, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output not yet decisive.
We try to change that, working on real three-dimensional display systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We must release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, this requires that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much more easily.
And first and foremost, we should get rid of these stupid Virtual-Reality-Helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It is popular, but is it not overvalued?
- It is certainly not a one-size-fits-all solution, since it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and concise gestures rather than expansive ones.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a wristband that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but theoretically it could be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gesture and speech.
- How?
- We would ask you, for example, to give you this jacuzzi?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- Usually I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot achieve at a given time?
- Not necessarily, but it is a matter of mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future, we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that will enable people ’ s reactions to be recorded more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, as they offer good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 Megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the x- and y-, but also along the z-axis has to be considered.
The speed and number of frames per second are also important.
The human movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are too little, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed in our lab in Redmond a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay between 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction between man and machine.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more pictures per second.
- Would it not be necessary to increase the number of cameras?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or reinforce the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
A flexible system similar to Kinect would be nice, in which we could play with different camera angles to see how this helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that, with regard to the application of the technology of augmented reality in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always have a smartphone in your hands when you are on the move, but I think the following: The best variant would be a "changing" expanded reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and therein lies their strength (private things only you can see), but at the same time also their weakness, because an expanded reality with glasses prevents that you can work together with others on virtual objects.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark of Iron Man, but also to ordinary mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often speak of augmented reality as the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection surface.
It perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving something tangible to the "images in the air", for example, the interference of some directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is, creates a feeling that is currently still as weak as if someone were blowing over the ball of the hand.
There are also wrist bands that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outsmart the brain?
Let it think that it feels what it should feel when it is seeing something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
This is another task that we will have to contend with for a long time to come, namely to make a person who is physically in an enclosed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), mobile platforms and large spheres.
So far, the brain can be tricked only moderately, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: for many topics, we are only at the beginning.
Taste instead of culture - rosbalt.ru
Rosbalt continues the "Petersburg Avant-Garde" project, which is dedicated to city dwellers who form the avant-garde of art and culture.
High-ranking representatives of the Petersburg art scene, whose successes extend beyond the borders of the city and which often find recognition in Europe without being known in the rest of Russia, have already landed on the select list.
The new hero of Rosbalt is the extravagant artist Kirill Miller.
The whole town knows Kirill Miller, the bearded man dressed in red, who can be seen at the Russian Museum, at the summer garden, at the scene of meetings or at openings.
Wherever Kirill Miller ’ s paintings are exhibited, they attract large crowds.
Kirill Miller is one of the typical Petersburg social-philosophical artists who create new myths.
Kirill Miller is a luminous figure of the Petersburg avant-garde at the end of the 80s and the beginning of the 90s.
He is also a man of the city and, by his presence on the street, brings a smile to the faces of his fellow citizens and puts them in a good mood.
Recently he grabbed a barrel organ and became the St. Petersburg barrel organ player, as he finally felt ready for this difficult role in terms of his artistic life, his philosophy and his image.
- Kirill, why are you always in red and not, for example, in yellow or turquoise in the city on the road?
I chose the color red as a fashion designer, who deals with the optics and the image.
In this world, red is the compromise between artist, image consultant and society.
In society, anything that deviates from the Gray Norm causes aggression and bad behavior.
But I want to enter into conversation with the people through my provocations.
Each of my past provocations was an invitation to talk.
- When did you know that you had to become a painter?
- At an exhibition in the Palace of Culture Nevsky, where my works were exhibited.
I understood that I had to go this way.
Then the time of the old free, but not officially recognized painters came to an end, and new and free painters like me were incomprehensible.
I became friends with the painters of the new generation, that is, with the representatives of the "Gazonevshina"; this resulted in "Pushkinskaya 10", and then it was over.
I am drawn to the theatre, to fashion, to music, to everything but literature.
- And all this united in your kind of clinic... - It was important to me to be at the centre of St. Petersburg culture, where the best creative artists should gather.
In 1995, I occupied one room at Pushkinskaya 10, and before the renovation works, there was an artistic club for Bohemian music, the House of St. Petersburg Bohemians.
Many were born there: N.O.M., Tequilajazzz, and I also remember how Schnur came there with his project "Ucho Van Goga".
Schnur and his friends sang simple songs to the playback, wore tight jerseys and to them belonged the composer Igor Wdowin.
When the group started to play live, it became "Leningrad".
Trachtenberg moderated many programs before the time of "Hello Galli".
We gave them Trachtenberg, and it began his great career, but he learned the basics from us.
Also the gallery "D 137" or the club "Griboedov" have their origin in the art clinic.
Our employees and regular guests went there.
I am a hero of the last century, when culture still meant something.
In the year 2000, there was a poll in the press about the award "Personalities of our city".
I won in the category "Artist of the Year" and with that I reached the climax.
It is not easy to work according to old rules in new times; I am a man of truth, honesty and culture of the past century.
Nowadays it is easy to become famous, but culture and popularity are not the same: you can be famous without making a cultural contribution.
- Your works have an unmistakable style.
- Many of my pictures are real pearls and express clearly the actuality and sharpness of the thoughts.
I will have an exhibition with the theme "The Russian Museum as Clowns".
Clowns are timeless.
I used to be social, but now it hurts and scares me to be that way.
In a clown it all blurs and loses its tragedy.
I love the grotesque, and I have grotesque ideas.
For example, let us save the world by prescribing that everyone has to dress up completely.
Now everyone pays attention to the clothes and orients himself on the outside and not on the inside of the person.
But perhaps one should not shake hands with a person, but spit in his face.
The deception disappears through the disguise.
- Recently we saw you in the role of the urban barrel organ player. - A cultural city should have such a hero.
Who, if not me?
- Can commercial art be beautiful?
- Nowadays commercial art must be cautious, considerate and flattering.
We see the disintegration of cultures.
People used to form large groups: the bohemians loved one and the common people the other.
Now there are micro-communities and it is difficult to please everyone.
I ’ m not a hundred dollars ’ note that everyone likes.
Now you have to decide who you will like.
Now every cult star has about 100 followers.
- Several thousand come to the performances of Stas Mikhailov!
- Abandoned women come to him, where the sexual-social sphere plays a role.
For cultural reasons, 300 people come and not 10 thousand, so there is less management, money and everything is ruined.
I have supporters, and the most important thing is not to deceive them and not to destroy what has been achieved.
In my youth I painted such pictures, which even hung with a collector in a row with the works of Falk and Larionov.
I started with pictures that normally don ’ t come until the end of my career.
Nowadays, there are often misunderstandings.
It is called: spiritual culture and consumer culture.
Consumption has no culture at all, that is something quite different.
I am a person of the past culture and I grew up with artists who lived in poverty and died in poverty and refused money in order to paint.
That is the culture I support.
- Kirill, what is missing Petersburg?
- Good cultural experts.
They say: servants of culture.
But not all of them can deal with culture.
It was different with the real Tsars, for the Tsars perhaps did not understand much about culture, but they understood that real experts are necessary.
