Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with inhabitants on board set off in search of a replacement planet.
In order to save mankind, the important question arises, how we can propagate in weightlessness or on the substitute planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Namely Mars and Venus", says the scientific assistant of the Astronomical Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are relatively friendly to life, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first addressed the question of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Experiments with plants had already been carried out half a century earlier.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit was not at all different from the earthly species.
This was followed by the cultivation of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to investigate the effects of weightlessness on the development of embryos.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to be able to stand on its legs and start moving," says Vladimir Sykhev, head of the laboratory at the Institute for Medical Biological Problems RAN.
Without a solid ground the chicks spilled over wildly.
Ten hours later, the newborn ’ s instincts became completely numb.
The chicks did not react to light and sound.
Four days later, they simply died.
"We let chicks hatch twice and then stopped the whole thing, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sykhev says about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite "Bion" will contain only same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that had already been fertilized and sent into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was with the bio-satellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research must continue," says Vladimir Sykhev.
After landing, the space rats had offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals, which are torn from its natural habitat, simply cannot follow its reproductive-instinct.
In contrast to animals, humans could do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most precious thing that mankind possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Will it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"After all, no one answered this question," says space veteran Vakhtang Vachnadze.
In June 1964, only one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Savitskaya, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there is still a risk.
We have only very few cosmonauts, where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more dangerous it is, even during flights into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valery Polyakov, Hero of the Soviet Union and Hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet mankind must look for new paths in biotechnology, radiation protection, and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory in the cosmonaut preparation center is a compulsory station during flight preparation.
Here in a state of limbo, the cosmonauts gain routine for their work in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Although adults find water pleasant, it is an alien environment; but infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if little Ichtyander were witnessing life on land emerging from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in amniotic fluid in the mother ’ s womb for about 9 months and the fact that it can then get used to water more easily.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks pass from birth until the first swim.
"This is not enough time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
Whereas weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman cannot do without gravity.
In a state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles shrink enormously and thus the ability to squeeze out the child also decreases.
All right, let us avoid this by using birth initiating aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is Valery Polyakov's not insignificant question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling an earth attraction, an organism cannot form a skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in an endurance suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of elementary importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are undertaking together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will result in the birth of a disabled person, a completely unadapted person," predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestov.
So far, the birth of children in space has been a mere theory.
At some point, however, it will become reality when the inhabitants of the earth set off in their spaceships to a distant planet that will be the home of their offspring born in space.
NKÚ Inc. chief: Control of Black System Failed by Political Debt
The Czech Republic has good supervisory bodies and adequate laws in connection with public contracts, but falls behind in their application.
In an interview for Aktuálně.cz, the Vice-President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ), Miloslav Kala, said the following.
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think that is the case with us," comments Kala on the current situation.
A similar conclusion seems to be reached by joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he cites the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "black" system.
The Prime Minister recently said that ODS would not harass entrepreneurs with controls, so is the system banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is forbidden by law, it cannot simply be the head of the government who comes and impedes the activities of the Office of Control, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law," notes Kala.
At the meeting of the Control Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech and German project in which the laws of both countries on public contracts were compared.
What exactly was this about?
This is a parallel test, which we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it is a question of the European legislature determining how public contracts are to be handled, which is what national legislation builds on, and, finally, there is the actual practical application.
All of this we have compared with each other, and although the examination is not yet completed, we have been able to find extremely interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws here are perhaps even more "strict and perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to constantly draw up new and more precise rules, but that we must also look at the actual application of the law.
To what extent can the project be of help to you? What does this project imply for you?
It is precisely this kind of joint monitoring that could help us to stop constantly striving to improve legislation and to lower and balance thresholds, when this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Profitability means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
However, lowering the thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this objective.
It may even be the case that we are burdening the system in this way only with excessive 'paperwork', and those who are looking for loopholes in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
You talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech procurement law.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German equivalent of the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which has a similar structure to ours and also has a college that is formed slightly differently. In principle, however, both authorities work in a similar way.
The competencies are also comparable to a certain extent, although Germany is a federal state, i.e. these audit offices also exist in the individual Länder - this is how the German system differs from ours.
The FRG may control only federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds, which in our country are administered by the districts and municipalities, are there subject to the control of the provincial audit offices.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would be reluctant to compare this without specific data. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as a role model in some respects, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the auditors are better?
Certainly not, but as I said, I do not particularly like comparisons of this kind.
It should also be noted that those countries which are an example to us also face problems.
Otherwise, they would not be cooperating with our authority, would they not?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what significance did the amendment of the Public Procurement Act have for your authority, do you feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our audits.
Since our controls are retroactive, we must expect a certain delay here.
So far, we have felt more of an impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control instrument "Identification of risks of inefficiency" and with this we have examined and analysed almost 14,000 public contracts - here the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc.
Do you see the adoption of this law as rather positive, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become 'stricter' and can no longer be complied with.
Under the previous rules, audited persons are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of a regional policy operational programme, the Regional Council) to the effect that any failure to comply with the procurement law amounts to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have made a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system merely puts even greater pressure on bureaucracy.
Where is the way out?
First of all, let us say which way is not the right one.
The Prime Minister said recently that the ODS would not bother the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black" system - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black-and-white system now prohibited or allowed?
A law must be valid, and if something is forbidden by law, then it is not easy for the President of the Government to come and obstruct the activities of the Office of Control, whose duty it is to monitor compliance with the law.
He can say, "We change the law and let the thing go," but he can't say that we pretend there is nothing.
The Public Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and that is also right for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best bid is excluded solely because of formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we lack.
