Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to gather positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world taking place in less than a month?
This is one of the disaster reports to which we humans are so keen to jump.
With our band The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a nationwide charity event, which we have been planning for two years.
For this, we want to utilize the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which is predicted for 21 December at 11: 10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place at the same time from 21: 00 in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
The end of the concerts is said to be around the time that the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which lies in a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to reflect with the public on the state in which we will once hand this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and key chains against the end of the world, with the purchase of which people can also support us via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap together with other performers has also recorded the so-called Hymn against the end of the world with the title "Weltuntergang fällt aus".
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The hymn is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts simultaneously.
The anthems will also be broadcast live by Czech television.
The lyrics of the hymn are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X also sings with...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we organize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It turned out that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What is the purpose of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible educational center Studeo, on which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap in the Jedlička-institute.
Students of the Jedlička institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we want to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička institute, a separate building is to be constructed, into which we will move with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you use to select them?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May, we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - when we are in the USA - would also like to combine this with appearances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not exactly small, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organisationally?
It is not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be carried in the luggage compartment. In addition, we must of course carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Your trips abroad will give you a comparison of what accessibility is like in the individual countries, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than here, we have witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its infancy in the East.
Opposite Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible for disabled people. There, it is still unusual when someone is travelling alone in a wheelchair in the city centre.
There it is not even self-evident that one leaves a wheelchair user for example in the elevator.
Fortunately, associations are also being set up there to try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things in which we are lagging behind...
It should also be noted, however, that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move independently in public spaces, go to museums, use toilets, etc.
But it is not common for a large group of handicapped people to take an active part in social events. In this respect, we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect among the public and accessibility is one thing, but it is only when major athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks that things will really start to change.
So far these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička ’ s institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensive.
And since I am a musician myself and play the saxophone, among other things, I founded a music society together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, likes to say, it got a bit out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us and we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and it is not visible to the outside world, your own achievement in a certain sense does not exist.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good lecturers, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to bring The Tap Tap this far?
Right from the start, I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are few truly unique things, and I dare say that tap tap is part of it.
The first impression the viewer usually gets is of course pity; that is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a fully-fledged life, provided that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, it is progress not only for them, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as one hears from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise on many things and must also demand a certain degree of discipline.
In my opinion, this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic concepts, and when they discover that they have to rehearse twice a week, complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But that ’ s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go. You can ’ t prevent that.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
