Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this space agency at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the member countries of the European Space Agency (ESA), making it the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland ’ s path into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were occupied with space travel, although they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics", donated by Robert Esnault and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-renowned contribution to the development of space flight was also honoured by the fact that one of the craters on the away side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railroad was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or to brake the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with missiles.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents handed down that research had reached the stage of practical tests.
However, research was interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a draft of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the trade press, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa "Krzywoblocky" appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo, Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity its work was terminated at the beginning of the war.
More articles on space flight appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company comes in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to space travel.
Prof. M. Subotowicz's article proposes the creation of a space company.
At that time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was foreseeable that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Agency (PTA) endeavoured to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member as early as the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became the deputy chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM, 1A, was built, and in 1959, in the Błędów, the desert, flight tests began with the two-stage rocket RM, 2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be in a position to carry out real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In the year 1962 however the further development was stopped.
Successor of the first missiles of the type RM was the in the years 1962 to 1965 developed meteor "1" rocket.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket have been developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differ in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a transport compartment with a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor -1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor -1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Aeronautics Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor ܢ 2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Thereafter, the versions Meteor, 2H and Meteor, 3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ’ s accession to the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960, followed two years later by the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
The repeal of the Public Service Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court annulled the law on community service.
This decision provoked a lively public discussion.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberal economies of the EU and the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
Ultimately, this means that economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labour (wages), there are price tensions.
This term refers to a situation in which the manufacturer tries to compete economically by importing cheap goods, "undercutting" competition, in order to gain a larger share of the market and increase its profits.
On a large scale, this means for most companies moving their manufacturing operations abroad, or buying cheap, or giving up business, resulting in high unemployment in countries with comparably high labor costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility, and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is exacerbated by the fact that employers are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes, thereby compensating for the economic and social damage they cause to society as a whole.
This situation is well known, so specific statistics are superfluous here.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments leave their own people at the mercy of private capital, regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to existing laws.
The aim of these measures is to force their own people to accept the dictates of private capital, particularly in the area of wages.
This is being done, on the one hand, through economic constraint in the face of long-term unemployment, and, on the other, through the curtailment of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as widening disparities between rich and poor.
In Germany, there have been public food dispensaries for the poor for several years that are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of those affected is already running into millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which workers receive such a low wage that the state has to increase their income to the subsistence level.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of auxiliaries employed by the German Bundestag.
Austerity measures by virtually all the EU ’ s southern states will undoubtedly amount to the same condition, with people forced to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) under the pressure of a catastrophic fall in their social level, or to starve on the margins of society for a pittance, hoping that private investment capital will eventually flow into the country.
Here, of course, the question arises as to where this capital comes from.
If it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital simply stays out, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco, Egypt, or Africa in general, workers work for a fraction of European wages.
This concerns the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim ad nauseam that the state must not participate with capital in its own economy, and that planned economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital persists narrowly in its position that the state must not intervene in the economy in a directive manner.
But then one has to ask oneself whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
Proof of this is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual advantage, legislation in which practically everything is criminal but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that due to a lack of finance, a State Ministry entrusts private legal entities closely linked to industry with the preparation of draft laws.
These bills will then be passed by the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer emanates from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously the liberal democracies are quickly finding themselves in a situation such as that described by Appian in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in disarray and the offices were occupied by force.
Against bribes, by illegal creeping of advantages or with stone and sword.
The corruption grew rampant and the people went to the elections with votes already bought "..." People of character did not apply for office, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this decline "..." People began to really talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was an autocracy, and that a strong man had to be elected "... Appian thought of Pompey, but the strong man was finally Caesar, who permanently replaced democracy with autocracy.
Today's society, as in ancient times, is based on the ruthless preference of one's own advantage, without paying any attention to the interests of society as a whole.
By its very nature, private capital is incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, now as then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not at all committed to deeper reforms.
The cause of the rise of fascism and communism must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalisation of the economies of the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today ’ s perspective, the demise of these regimes in favor of liberal democracies can be seen as some pause, with the next round already looming.
What is particularly catastrophic is the fact that today's elites are completely ignorant of the possible future loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, of the humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing and of the crimes against humanity that we know from past and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Service Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to lower the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase the state ’ s participation in the economy, increase citizens ’ influence on the government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
