The movie Argo: When it's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamic student protesters occupied the US American Embassy in Tehran, taking 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the ousted Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution to the United States, which had held patronage over his regime for decades.
The American administration had no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the ensuing fiasco in the violent attempt to free hostages only made matters worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days of negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The Iranian debacle contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter ’ s defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that brought the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, succeeded in bringing the refugees from Iran, aided by an extravagant story to conceal their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew who allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by Tony Mendez, an expert on "exfiltration", also made Hollywood's collaboration necessary.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret, and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Afflecks Film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time it is also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar play such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the relaxed passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable restart of his career with this film.
A scoffed at actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the thriller Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck ’ s first film that is not set in the director ’ s native Boston.
The sense for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that distinguished this director ’ s previous films from Hollywood ’ s standard.
Affleck proves this feeling also in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have actually taken place - the opening sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping reality a little - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes, in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted from a phone call in America, or the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too broad dispersion, caused by the necessity of having to show too much in action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are by no means alone in the film.
Affleck ’ s film loses some of its traction as a result. It is a film that one can follow with a certain interest, appreciating the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 1970s.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day and as a proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient secret services are.
Guidelines for inflating balloons, for bananas and for the circus
This year, the server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which publishes an annual survey on the most absurd bank charges, has decided to organise the competition "Most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"This is the idea behind the plan recently put forward by the EU to introduce a 40% quota for women in the management of large European companies," Patrik Nacher, who is in charge of organising this survey, told the newspaper Právo.
Among the absurdities nominated, for example, is the ruling by the European Court of Justice on the unification of insurance rates for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place by the end of February 2013 ", informed Nacher.
Among the controversial EU regulations are the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which is damaging to nature as a result, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain a relatively small amount of this hazardous substance, and the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
In the past, criticism has also been levelled at the de facto ban on the use of the term 'butter spread' or the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under pressure from this or that trade and industry lobby, whose claims are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member countries (for example, the Czech Republic is currently attempting to use a veto threat to enforce the claims of Czech banks).
Lobby ’ s interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest trading class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not exhibit any “curvature anomaly ”.
The European Commission defended itself with the argument that it merely harmonised the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
The EU has already softened the standards for fruit and vegetables, in the face of opposition from some countries, by pointing out that the existing directives would result in a waste of food.
One candidate for the victory in this poll may be last year ’ s EU regulation, which, according to balloons, must be sold with a note stating that children under the age of eight may not inflate the balloon without adult supervision.
The EU cited an American study which, according to Luftballons, is the leading cause of the suffocation of children.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to the age of 14 when using fairground streams.
There are also strange ideas at home
Relatively absurd is also a directive that affects the European officials themselves - anyone who has an official function in the EU cannot use the name FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) because of the sensitivity of the subject for Greece.
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com nominated in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire apart from the above-mentioned absurdities also the EU regulation on the scope of food stocks in the territory of a member country.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks that was allowed to be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our EU accession.
For example, the Czech Republic then exceeded the specified volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a large fine.
The survey organizers were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or by the idea of funding applications for grants.
These ideas did not come from Brussels, however, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by having no sea.
We will apply to the EU for reimbursement, "said the then Minister of Agriculture, Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that the grain harvest was very high and the state warehouses were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another route to seaports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
The European Commission finally went so far as to accommodate the Czech Republic by organising a call for tenders for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (U.S. DEU), offered subsidies for applications for subsidies to the municipalities. Specifically, this should include funds for the preparation of subsidy applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations may easily be the target of criticism in the Member States, the efforts of the EU to regulate and thus also to ensure the effectiveness and development of the European Union as a whole deserve more recognition, according to some experts.
A more serious problem, according to these experts, is rather EU funding for projects that have absolutely nothing in common with deepening European integration, but which have been forced by individual member states in the budget negotiations.
Emotions in this country are also aroused by the fact that, similar to other member countries, the Czech Republic has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for traditional products and does not always win this battle.
After a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky", the Tuzemský rum, whose tradition here dates back to the 19th century, but our manufacturers had to rename it "Tuzemák".
The designation rum may only be used for products made from sugar cane distillate, not for products made from sugar beet.
In the official list of products registered in the EU, the world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, Lübeck marzipan and Parma ham are now joined by Karlovy Vary rusk, Pohořelice and Třeboň carp, and Saas hops.
With an EU trademark, Pardubice gingerbread or Hořice rolls can boast.
“People want me to save the Republic, but I ’ m just an amateur, ” says Okamura.
Senator, how do you come up with the idea of running for President?
I do not want to be a senator or a president.
If everything worked smoothly in our country, I would not be standing for election anywhere.
But I can no longer see the republic being plundered for 20 years, thieves walking freely while people are being raised in taxes and retirement age.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something I do not like, I try to propose a solution to change that.
And since I am already over 40, and independent and non-partisan, I have no other way of influencing things than to run for the office of senator or president.
You made it into the Senate and then made your way to the castle.
Are you not turning your back on your voters?
I have been telling myself all the time that I will take up the fight for the castle after the result of the Senate elections.
Later I clarified this and said that I would run for president if I were elected senator.
But my goal is not the function. The function is an instrument with which I can realize my visions.
For this I need as much influence as possible and a mandate that is as strong as possible.
The difficulty, however, is not only that we, as a people, grumble in the pub and in front of the television, but that we kill anyone who wants to make a difference.
Then there are the media, which want to rob you of your honour and confuse the freedom of the word with the freedom to lie.
It was said of me, for example, that I would bribe journalists or that I was an advisor to Jiří Paroubek.
Let ’ s talk about your visions.
You started the fight for the castle with the thesis of material and criminal liability of politicians as well as with retroactive property declarations of more than 20 million crowns.
To do this, you need to change laws.
As President, you have no competence in this respect, and only the Senate as a whole can bring forward legislative proposals.
How do you intend to solve this problem?
As an ordinary citizen, I have fought to ensure that the guide remains a free trade and this has been enforced.
The problem is petty-minded politics - if someone comes from the right or the left with a good proposal, it is deliberately rejected, and that only stops the population.
As an independent non-party, I have much greater potential to win support from all parties represented in Parliament.
My advantage is that, without pigeonholing and party dogma, I can take from any party what is best for our country.
Do you, as a person, see yourself more to the right or the left in politics?
From a Czech perspective, it seems to me that people tend to see me on the left.
For me, this is right and left thinking but completely unimportant.
For me, it is important that we move forward.
I am not interested in whether someone belongs to the left or the right; I want to connect people.
I always publicly support any good approach, even if it comes from the KSČM or the ODS, and I will also oppose bad ideas.
You dislike someone calling you a populist.
But do you not confirm what you have just said?
When you draw up a business plan in a company, you also have an ideal goal and a vision.
And this is what you want to approach.
This can be called populism, but all the proposals I have spoken about are already working in the world, or they have been discussed by important experts.
Without your support in Parliament, however, all that remains for you are slogans.
And you will not get very far in politics in the long term.
Or do you think that if you talk to people long enough, you will be able to enforce material and criminal liability, for example?
I have no other option.
To convince politicians, journalists and the public and try to get them on our side to achieve these goals.
As President, I would have no problem asking the leaders of the parliamentary parties, live on television, to legislate on material and criminal liability for politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors.
And the persons addressed would then have to say, if necessary, why they reject this.
A strong personality pointing out grievances can put pressure on the political scene.
Just take the direct election of the President, which was the result of public pressure.
I say clearly that I am an amateur; I am neither a genius nor an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my views and visions.
I have only just begun with politics and am trying to find the support of the majority for my programme.
I always try to judge things myself; and if it doesn't work, I will go back to the private sector in six years' time.
That sounds a little as if Okamura should save the Czech Republic.
I am not a savior.
I know that I do not achieve anything on my own, so I have talked to several well-known people about whether they also want to stand for the Senate.
For example, I spoke to Radim Jančura, who declined due to overwork.
I also supported the investigative journalist Jana Lorencová, who exposed the fraud in the trade in light heating oil.
I started my candidacy on the assumption that people are deeply dissatisfied, but now I am no longer sure.
Sixty per cent of those entitled to vote did not go to the elections at all, and those who did went mostly elected representatives of the establishment.
In the Senate, then, we are only two independents.
People have chosen such a senate composition that changes will be very difficult to enforce.
Nevertheless I will fight for my visions, e.g. for the direct election of the mayors and district governors.
Are you thinking about forming your own party?
I have not thought about this yet, because I do not have time to review the past of any potential party member, nor do I have the money for it.
I do not even have money for the presidential campaign; my transparent account is only CZK 20,000.
You have no money?
You talk about declarations of assets, what would your position be?
My personal wealth is estimated at about CZK 60 million.
In Prague, I have a piece of land worth 25 million, an apartment worth about 10 million, another for 8 million, an art collection worth about 10 million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Škodu Superb worth about a million, and then I have a few million on my account.
By the way, the Aston Martin was a child's dream - I always liked James Bond driving in the car, being gallant to women and at the same time fighting against evil.
You drive an Aston Martin, have a fortune of 60 million and have no money for your campaign?
You say that you want to change the republic, but you do not want to invest your own money in it.
That is not very convincing.
I don ’ t have 15 million for the campaign.
Should I run into debt?
I have already invested 2.5 million in the campaign.
The fact that I don ’ t have any sponsors shows that my program probably doesn ’ t arouse much interest.
And I am not obliged to finance the campaign from my own resources.
The cost of the campaign is basically covered by my salary as a senator.
But I could not live on the salary of the senators alone; for example, I could not finance the English school for my son, which costs 30,000 per month.
If I just wanted to make money, I wouldn ’ t run for anything.
So do you continue to work as an entrepreneur to make a living?
Did you not say that you will reduce these activities?
But that has nothing to do with the level of salary.
As promised, I have partially scaled back my activities.
Thus e.g. my deputy becomes managing director of the travel agency in the spring.
People want to see me as the Samaritan who saves the republic.
But I have to live on something.
What monthly income were you used to as an entrepreneur?
Approximately 200,000 to 400,000, and that continues to be the case.
As President, however, I would stop my business altogether.
