The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the mind - the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
“I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there ’ s something interesting to see again, ” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by by the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, IT engineer at a large company nearby, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
They all have internet, iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one goes voluntarily to one of these old style libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town hardly in need of a visit at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000 inhabitants of the municipality have the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to reconstruct the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as beautifully brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to control the statistics: A library had to be created!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of daring bar charts and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual calmness and appeared at the 2003 Hearing competition with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around in amazement and shrugging their shoulders, the cheeky Maas piled up his exquisite souvenirs in size to form a pyramid and ended his actionist speech with the words: "Dear city council!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has been piled up.
It is part of a revitalisation project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This means that the faceless small town gate, which until then had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and a bewilderingly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to assume a dairy factory, is enriched by a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Book Eldorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that runs through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true joy of space and reading is revealed by climbing the topography on foot.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt brick floor and the elegant street lamps speak unmistakably the language of a public town square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
One is already looking out for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Usually the bookshelves are located along the façade, and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal, ” says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and turned the reading area inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle there are offices, the Internet ’ s library, chess club, environmental centre and building services centre.
A special joy are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall covering, sometimes parapet, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse Municipality, upon request from Standard.
And so one day, in a farm in Friesland, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, a thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and on fields for many years.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed into plates four centimetres thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells a bit like new cars and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you have reached the top.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long hike, the Literaturcafé will reward you not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide the atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
“You wouldn ’ t believe it, but this house is a model project in terms of ecology, despite the many glass surfaces, ” says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal energy.
Although the Bücherberg is under a glass lintel, the sun shines only briefly into the interior even on sunny days.
The broad glulam beams, which are perpendicular to the glass façade, serve as shading and absorb a large part of the solar radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic in the IT industry, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
And also TCM ’ s teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg Spijkenisses “long overdue soul ”.
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
This will initially fill the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully stocked - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept worked.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that now, thanks to our invitation, every resident has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it is only for decoration.
Thus MVRDV succeeded in the supreme discipline, which one calls in the technical jargon identity endowment.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as it may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US and European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first signalled that it would vote against the application for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious, owing to its special relationship with Israel.
At the same time, however, I do not believe that it supports the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that is true.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, moving away from a policy that was, so to speak, managed by the USA towards a German foreign policy.
Making matters worse, Europeans lack a coherent and coherent policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still trying to play their role, but they are on the way to a more 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy like that of France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy actually mean from a German perspective?
It shows a willingness to take positions on national interests that are independent of those of the USA or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, in other words by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ’ s economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other major powers, and so Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to offend the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That certainly matters.
But I would not want to attach too much importance to that either, that is not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the USA for the German position.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic rupture as on the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even win some respect for itself.
After all, it signals that, as an international player, it must be taken seriously and its interests taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has spoken out clearly in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a good deal of secretive sympathy for the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot publicly represent this position, of course.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not all that enthusiastic about Netanyahu ’ s policies.
Is Germany finding it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the EU ’ s most important partners on the other?
I think that is what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead push things from their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in future, Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe towards a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, if only because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans understand that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international player? Does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or is Germany still finding it difficult to lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it still finds it difficult to play a greater role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, every time Germany assumes a greater role, various anti-German feelings become free.
That does not make it easy for the Germans.
That's the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this sense, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It has to be receptive to different neighbours and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the USA in European politics is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment; who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, it is unpleasant and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, DC, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America conduct joint research on the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
