Facts on Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human pappiloma viruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies are parasitic STIs.
Who are the main stakeholders?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
According to the German Institute for Medical Research, at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia are sexually transmitted infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungi), gonorrhea and human pappiloma viruses.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in Germany is comparatively low - nevertheless, around 20 percent of new HIV infections are attributable to this group.
Chlamydia infection is much more common in adolescents than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15-25.
In Germany, human pappiloma viruses are also common among adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are reportable.
The number of syphilis cases has more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011, according to Robert Koch ’ s Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has declined since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2,700 cases.
That is about a tenth less than the year before.
Which symptoms indicate venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort with urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain as well as blisters or warts.
However, they often cause no pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of contagion, but do not provide 100% protection.
In some cases, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through smear infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially for frequently changing sex partners.
If diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and long-term consequences avoided.
