They demanded from Morsi, "Clean the land!" and affirmed, "The Koran is our constitution."
A battle for sovereignty over symbolic Tahrir, where everything began, would likely have created a civil war-like state.
Obviously, Morsi ’ s supporters did not want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood declared that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the supporters had expressed themselves loudly and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people decide at the ballot box in which direction the country should go.
A majority in favour of the Islamists ’ draft is considered certain.
"The word human rights does not even occur"
Hafez Abu Saeda is outraged by this forced constitutional process, which was supposed to run until February and involve all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and head of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution", he complains in conversation with the "Welt am Sonntag".
Morsi ’ s extension of power to all three powers in the state caused the lawyer to resign.
These measures are blatant violations of democratic rules and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the President has de facto suspended it," complains Saeda.
But democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels left alone, even by the international community, which views the ideological struggle along the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could take revenge.
A demonstrator on the Tahrir warns: "You breed a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most malodorous fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards - not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country ’ s secret to success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty nauseating fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And leave them there a week.
One has to imagine the nose-numbing smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway ’ s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that persistent smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is a salt-sprinkled trout that is fermented in water for up to a year, depending on how smelly the fish is.
When in Norway the darkness comes over the country and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk" general.
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and drink large amounts of alcohol.
"Some people like Aquavit more than Rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirit can suppress the smell.
I taste some snacks.
If you avoid bringing the Rakfisk near the nose, it is not bad - like Sushi, which has had a long bus ride.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, far poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling facilities and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in the autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was taken out after long fermentation and consumed - undoubtedly with the help of senses steamed with alcohol.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the US.
Today the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a flourishing labour market, high wages and comprehensive health care.
Even Sweden, the old rival that not so long ago was far richer than Norway, is pouring in immigrants.
Rakfisk is considered an important part of Norwegian history - an essential, if strong smelling, part.
It is one of the more expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs 10 Euros.
Norway doesn ’ t make it into the world press often, and most people don ’ t seem to mind.
They still hate to call Anders Breivik by his name - the racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, reference is made only to the "22 July incident".
Norwegians have a hard time accepting that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, the growth of one of the world ’ s largest oil and gas industries has been largely responsible for Norway ’ s current wealth.
"But oil is not the only reason why we are doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with ripe rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blond hair and piercing blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Her English, like that of most people here, is flawless.
We are not very pretentious, we do not like boasting.
Norway has been very careful with its oil wealth – a large proportion of the industry ’ s earnings will be invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the Great Depression, when everyone threw money around that they did not have, Norway kept its purse tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And of course eat Rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and line up for another court - I have had enough of Rakfisk.
So a moose burger is definitely something else. I like the juicy meat.
But in the evening the stinky fish is on the menu again.
The hotel I ’ m staying at is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk ’ s dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most aromatic – fish.
There is a Live 'TV' circuit to a bow-clad showmaster who is surrounded by dishes with rakfisk.
The spectacle is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor? Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard".
One claps and laughs.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But perhaps it is the severe haze of the whole fish.
Mexico ’ s Enrique Pena Nieto Faces Difficult Start
As Mexico ’ s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, the BBC ’ s Will Grant analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is an ever-congested city, but on Monday, a steel ring was erected that closes off several important traffic routes into the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disrupt commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico ’ s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential bandage and take over the leadership of the nation.
It faces a complex task.
Mexico has been economically successful under Felipe Calderón ’ s outgoing government, but the country is gripped by a drug war that has already claimed 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My government is strongly committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this objective.
Before joining the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A Direct Man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents attribute to him the development of tourism and the development of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can take one of the motorways that Pena Nieto had built, which are a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques bearing his name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for Pena Nieto's party, the PRI.
In particular, as regards security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change, which our country so badly needs.
After 81 years in power, Vicente Fox replaced the PRI in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the opposition ’ s accusations that the new president lacks substance.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But, on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway overpasses and is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are decisively urban.
Earlier this year, the military was turned on to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, the corpses of dozens of murdered women have been left on a wasteland near a large landfill.
During Governor Pena Nieto's term of office, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that surpasses even that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Pena Nieto ’ s critics believe that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of feminicide during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the rundown neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the rigidity of the corpses had already set in.
While her mother is telling her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall, next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But it is exactly this, according to the family, that she has been denied so far.
The authorities have treated me as if I were a gossip, a troublemaker, a nagger.
They want their verdict to be simply accepted and shut up.
“But that ’ s not possible when there were so many mistakes and omissions, ” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential bandage on Saturday, he is also taking on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to pay particular attention to this problem during his tenure.
"As president, I hope he is as he was as governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
The prosecution claims that Bradley Manning did not complain of mistreatment
The prosecution contradicts Bradley Manning ’ s allegations that he was mistreated in prison
The hearing is about Mannings time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defence seeks to dismiss the charges on the basis of excessively harsh prison conditions
The corporal of the U.S. Army is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents
The prosecution tried on Friday to find out that army mate Bradley Manning - accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - missed several opportunities to complain about his alleged mistreatment in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Mann during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that there was no complaint about his treatment on records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Mann's nine months in Quantico, Virginia.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held on the basis of a defence motion to dismiss the indictment - Manning had already been punished sufficiently by the harsh prison terms - Manning testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In Friday ’ s hearing, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after meeting Manning during his detention in the Quantico military prison, where he had been detained from July 2010 to April 2011 under intensified detention conditions.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When asked about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole to be "very professional".
The forms, Fein said, contained no complaints of abuse, even though officers had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officers had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them. However, they had not been recorded.
“They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) ‘ no problems ’, and that didn ’ t necessarily mean that I didn ’ t say anything at all, ” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form several months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to downgrade his observation status on "injury prevention".
The military said that it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one step below suicide risk - to protect him and others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of the status of observation on injury prevention (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he had considered suicide and was unconscious because of the heat.
Not being allowed to know what is happening to him or to the outside world was a burden.
"My world shrank to Camp Arafjon, to that cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
They only allowed him a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and glasses.
Manning said he had tried to keep moving, because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down.
He had always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, he was woken up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning ’ s lawyer formally objected to treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth, Kansas military prison.
On Friday, the judge also questioned Manning about an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - he had to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during that count.
During Friday ’ s interrogation, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday Manning had testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night. He had previously tried to show an official that he was no danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could use the waistband of his underwear or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not do so.
That night, Manning said, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take his experience into account and drastically reduce his detention if he is convicted at his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offenses, while other charges considered to be too extreme are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend and the prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the regulations that apply to all detainees under the highest security measures in Quantico.
Manning was charged with favoring the enemy, illegally publishing intelligence on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all counts, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-Based American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants - they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just passed through the hall and arrived at the passport control, as perplexity set in.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure where to go.
I grew up in Central California and was called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves' Irish 'or my friends in New York call themselves' Italians'.
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's homeland there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I do not have the vocabulary of a native speaker, nor do I get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and queued up for extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when Mexico ’ s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all the issues that one would expect when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs, and trade.
Pena Nieto was also keen to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico rather than migrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc on the model of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue Mexico ’ s war against the drug cartels, even if he didn ’ t give any details.
Mexico ’ s relationship with the United States is complicated and resentful.
Most Americans probably never give a single thought to the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country ’ s leaders to surrender more than half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries, not minutes, memories of that event cannot be overlooked.
So, whenever a US government official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints – in the Mexican press and among the country ’ s elites – about Americans ’ harassment of their neighbor ’ s sovereignty.
And the children of Montezuma set out on the path of war.
And yet Mexico ’ s greatest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans who live in the United States.
Desire to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - was not given a chance in Mexico and emigrated northward.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people and we are faithful to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may have lived the American dream, attended good schools, and got good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we are living - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as for our loyalty, it is not.
This clearly applies to the United States.
We are also aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a monument to a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have gone.
And then we would not find ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and immigrated legally to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans resent that.
While she is a US citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they belong neither to nor to the country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but none of them is rooted.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and sections of the educated middle class want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Now.
That will not happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And, given the unfair distribution of income, rampant corruption, and drug violence, many of us are not so sure that this is a great country.
I'm afraid you have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That is fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must accept that some Mexican Americans have resentment of how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we are more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old Skirmishes, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Recent bloody events seem to nip such hope in the bud.
Amidst the usual blame game, countless buildings have been reduced to rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed - and for the first time rockets from Gaza have struck near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, while Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East around them is changing.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate may finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate given the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week ’ s fighting has strengthened the hardcore on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though its faction has suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are being killed and the 1.7 million Gazans are being crammed into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian Fatah group.
And Hamas ’ s leaders might conclude that they have time on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has attracted powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that was once Israel ’ s closest Muslim ally, has sided with Hamas – as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheering Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah holds power, to Syria, where increasingly Islamist rebels could face the toppling of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
Especially the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populous and important Arab country - on Israel's southern flank has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time for Hamas.
By contrast, the Brotherhood is allied with Hamas, and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas may prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas is no longer a danger.
Israel's Iron Dome missile defense system has proved its worth, and many of Hamas' rockets have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more calmly.
Diplomatically, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has fared well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers - not least thanks to the barriers that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which were declared illegal under international law, but are still being expanded.
Netanyahu is doing well. His Likud, a party allied with an even more militant group ahead of the election on January 22, led by Avigdor Lieberman.
Why pamper these deceitful Palestinians and give them their own state?
If they really had control of the West Bank, would they not be firing rockets, just like their comrades in Gaza?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will prevail, but the Arab Spring could thwart them.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and elsewhere have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties at home.
Israel ’ s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will do little to help the new Arab governments restore their economies.
The fact that the pragmatic President Morsi joined forces with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire may be a promising sign – perhaps symbolizing the beginning of a new era.
Israelis, too, should think longer.
As the rest of the Arab world takes tentative steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and this situation will only worsen with the growth of the Arab population.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel cedes territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more leverage to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Outside Arab nations should also persuade Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must play his part in getting Israel to negotiate.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, he also seems unwilling to participate.
But this is an unfortunate, short-sighted prospect.
The United States has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on unified cigarette packaging enter into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world ’ s first laws for standardized cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia. Brand logos and colors are replaced by neutral, olive green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and cigarette smoke infected infants and children.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, is from next Saturday.
This means that Australia is introducing the strictest regulations for tobacco packaging in the world.
The Australian federal government wants to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government is working on the basis of studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at the age of 26 are 99% likely to stop smoking afterwards.
"You can see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of the multinationals, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will have serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far greater quantities of these products on the roads of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone caps to cover the intolerable packaging has soared since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the law at the Australian Supreme Court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good business.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media is precisely the population targeted by the plan.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, prohibited them from sponsoring sports and forced most retailers to stop displaying cigarettes in stores. Now, tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned Internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“If you market tobacco and have only a small area left to promote your products, you can ’ t get around the Internet, ” says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has noticed an increase in experience reports on brands written by "ordinary people".
One has to ask oneself the question: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro so much that she even makes a video for it - or does a marketing agency have something to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of focusing on marketing, the industry is focused on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras, and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of them is doing much trade with Australia.
A WTO ruling is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to impose photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I simply ignore them.
"You simply take a cigarette and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box with a photo of an oral tumor on it.
Frankly, there is only one reason why I would stop, and that is my little girl.
James Yu, the operator of the tobacco trade "King of the Pack" in downtown Sydney, says that the uniform packaging has made it difficult to fill his shelves.
"It used to take me an hour to sort one shipment, now I need four," Yu says.
"The government should have banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said to ourselves okay, that's it, we'll close down," he adds, obviously angrily.
In a constantly electrified world it is nice to be bored sometimes
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane failed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think a bit about boredom.
I don't wanna lie
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty annoying - even if books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it is okay for us - and our children - to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thoughts, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us nowadays almost constantly stare at one screen or another, we no longer benefit from the advantages of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yes.
And no.
I will come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
Latin graffiti about boredom, dating back to the first century, adorns the walls of Pompeii ’ s house.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After reading research literature for a long time and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory job, but not being able to do it".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, on the other hand, there is no need to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two states may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think that we are bored, even if we just have difficulty concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume in which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups listened to a loud TV programme from the neighbouring room, which had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at a low volume, so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these noises at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could find no reason for them, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, Associate Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous job - "like looking for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract you and help you not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that wriggling and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat it by keeping people physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a roaring loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "scale of vulnerability".
On the scale are statements like "Many things I have to do are repeated and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, Professor of Psychology at the University of West Florida – especially when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But, in general, teenagers are a pretty wicked bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, Professor of Human and Community Development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adolescents at school and doing homework were bored, while 23% said they were bored when they were not at school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentage of boredom has increased or decreased.
However, he is certain that "the youth is felt to be particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their everyday life.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it leads to people taking extreme physical risks and falling prey to gambling or drugs in order to alleviate them, as studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain does not always know what to do best.
When you are bored and you use this energy to play the guitar and cook, you become happy.
But, while television can provide happiness in the short term, it will evaporate in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, it can dissuade them from boredom, but it has not taught them to talk or control themselves, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transfers from one situation to another".
The child not only learns to converse, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I do not believe that we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our aim should be to feel at home away from the constant flow of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we often have to be bored, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really looking for only one way to unwind and relax.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to occupy oneself once the noise has stopped."
Colorado has no clear guidance on the new marijuana law
19-year-old Anthony Orozco, a college student and soccer player, is standing trial in southeastern Colorado for an offense that will soon be legal in that state: owning a few marijuana smokers and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug utensils - cavaliers punishable by 100 US dollars each - and was given a court term.
"We are treated like criminals," says Orozco.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state ’ s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of misdemeanors revolving around marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington that approved similar measures.
Police authorities are no longer persecuting adults over 21 for small-scale possession, which will be allowed by law as soon as the new laws enter into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative districts of Colorado have announced that they will pursue existing marijuana cases and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new government-licensed marijuana shops from opening in their communities.
“This situation is developing so fast that I don ’ t know what will happen next, ” says Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
And Washington state regulators, too, scratch their heads helplessly.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, production, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline of 1 December 2013.
Washington believes that in any case Colorado is ahead of most states when it comes to regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical use and then legalized for personal use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is a good source of orientation," says Brian E. Smith, Washington State Spirits Regulator.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve as a rough guide.
"We do not have a real precedent to follow," he added.
The Washington Act, known as "I" 502, comes into force on December 6th, marking the end of a grey area in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical questions need to be clarified at this time - such as how the state requirement of "adequate access" to licensed marijuana should be reconciled with the ban on cannabis shops within 300 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds, and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be more difficult to find a site for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area," said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On 21 November, Chief Oates sent an e mail to his Aurora staff stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses against people over the age of 21, and that the police would not "immediately" seek criminal charges for these offenses.
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce municipal regulations to regulate growers of medical marijuana and continue to prosecute drug traffickers.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his agency would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to persuade consumers to withdraw.
Currently 119 people are being tried for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have been charged with other offences.
"Our authority has a duty to prosecute violations that were criminal offences at the time of the crime," Buck said in a statement.
Reactions are ambivalent even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer report adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to abandon all pending ownership procedures.
“I don ’ t think I ’ m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes, ” he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal use of marijuana with the complexities of the government and legal system.
And contradictory reactions across the state exposed a profound dichotomy among local officials over the great green experiment.
District prosecutors are a "cultural barrier," says Sean McAllister, a lawyer from Denver who represents defendants in court for marijuana crimes and serves as a local spokesperson for the national marijuana law reform organization.
"They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for not accepting legalization," he believes.
Colorado and Washington are the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana like alcohol as a national model case for legalizing drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an age of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government that will continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a federal offense.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will yield.
Despite several high-profile arrests of consumers and medical marijuana vendors, the federal government has allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states for the most part.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that, while detectives are unlikely to open doors to seize smaller quantities of drugs, they are likely to resist condoning legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado do not even wait for the federal authorities to act.
Before election day, some local governments approved moratoria for new marijuana, although it may not open until about a year from now.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the West, adopted a six-month ban that is expected to be adopted next week.
“We don ’ t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level, ” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this change in the law.
We are guided by what the community has chosen and not by what the state has chosen.
Many questions remain unanswered.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only university students today are being attacked for their views
It has always been my greatest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended what I once thought to be the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization — free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my arrival at Worscester College at the end of the eighties - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again and thus caused the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
In the Evening Standard it was said that I would have left, because I would have had a problem with fellow students having sex in the adjacent room.
Author A N Wilson mischievously explained that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I did, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my quite unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I was harassed for just one reason – one that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my late father, Woodrow Wyatt, had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I had been an advocate of the Conservative Party.
Why do I mention this now?
Now, according to recent reports, a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The organised and rising hatred of Tory ’ s Oxford students has now grown to such proportions that one group of them last week called for the same equality protection that benefits gays, the disabled, and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) of Corpus Christi College claim that they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" because of their political views.
They demand a place on their college ’ s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be expressed freely.
Their situation was aggravated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
Among the exhibits was graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the University of Oxford ’ s conservative student association, who rode a Rolls-Royce and boasted a silver-colored suit and silver cane.
In other universities, conservative students say they are seen as' scapegoats for the introduction of higher tuition fees'.
Luke Black, 20-year-old vice president of the University of Nottingham's conservative student association, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing leftist tendency in universities.
People think we are like the Bullingdon Club, without even getting to know each other. "
Samuel Roberts, 21, and a history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the petition for greater protection, believes that such a climate is “unpleasant. ” 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of the conservative Oxford Student Association, says she has observed growing disapproval among JCR members of students of the moderate right.
"This is a danger to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of its members," she says.
In my first few weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
An incredibly shy 18 year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
Hatred of the Conservative Party had peaked.
Last year, the university voted not to award Margaret Thatcher - a former student - an honorary title because of cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have frightened even Stalinists.
In the first days of the freshmen ’ s week, during which new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a foretaste of what will happen in the future.
My experience was that the tutors not only tolerated Tory ’ s mockery of students, but even gladly took part in it.
Political issues such as the miners ’ strike, privatization, and rejection of the government ’ s sanctions against South Africa ’ s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled upon it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite spiteful.
"Do Thatcher's supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
Tears rose in my eyes.
"I suggest that you take a few French lessons in your spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt growled at me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging down.
That evening, I was sitting alone at dinner in college when someone lightly tapped me on the shoulder.
It was an English student from the second year named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is harassed.
It is bad enough for me, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be worse for you.
Most Tory Tory first-year students pretend to be Labour Party supporters.
In a local pub I later tried to disguise myself.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick proved unsuccessful.
A young student in philosophy, politics and economics, who ironically attended Eton College, which is considered to be conservative, said to me: 'You are the daughter of a fascist pig'.
You are polluted.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They hit each other, right?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever manage to lead a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay ahead of me expanded into a purgatory of ostracism and isolation in my mind's eye.
The only tutor who openly proclaimed himself Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist, deterministic historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents ’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his forties, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said timidly.
They would never do that, not in my city of dreaming spires.
Even my Communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they just tease you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory's supporters, had yielded to the pressure and renounced his convictions.
During a tutorial the following week, in which another history tutor seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly faded away in shame, I admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me and called them "old idiots."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who nailed the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford ’ s career.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch newspaper.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You are welcome to call me a tearful flip-flop.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to endure such intimidation and malice in an educational establishment.
More tragically, it was Oxford - a university that not only spawned 14 Tory Prime Ministers, but hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to celebrity"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which opened this week in London, ABC talks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen, Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion designer.
Somerset House, the former residence of Isabel I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition of Valentino Garavani.
This was acknowledged by the designer at the opening of "Valentino - Master of Couture", a magnificent retrospective for which more than 130 dresses of haute couture have been assembled, created by his "Maison" in the last 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition concludes a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the stuffy and distant world of the nobility.
In the first room of this exhibition, which will be on view until 3 March, there is a large number of private letters and photos signed by the most exquisite aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Princess Marie Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social ascent from modest fashion designer in the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international jet set.
Being in love with the nobility does not have to be a disadvantage.
“At least they don ’ t kick their butts on your magnificent carpet, as some beautiful celebrities from pop music do, ” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen, Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s they lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all delighted when we were invited to his house in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, who is a close friend of forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to celebrity.
And yet he is a star.
Valeria Mazza in a dress by Valentino
Also the Argentinian model Valeria Mazza does not forget the charisma of the fashion designer.
Many years ago, after a fashion show at the Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went to his home for dinner.
We were about 20 people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
From every detail of his apartment, the decoration, the food and the music, one could recognize and feel his influence.
"Everyone who was invited felt important and loved," recalls the "TOP" model, which began her career at the 1995 Week of Haute Couture in Paris.
"He never goes out of fashion because his designs are works of art," she concludes.
Fashion Show of Origin
The life of Garavani is not a story of obsession, rather of mutual love.
He likes people with good education and the highest titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glorious 60-metre-long catwalk that suggests a role change: the user takes the model's place and walks along the catwalk to admire a dreamlike "audience" wearing Valentino's masterpieces, such as the dress Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristóteles Onassis, the costumes that Monica Vitti wore in "La Notte", or a wool and leather coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
In this audience of fashion dolls, names such as those of Sibilla de Luxemburgo, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette xen Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sofía von Habsburg shine.
Naty Abascal and the Fashion Designer, 2006
Many of these customers say that the first Valentino is like the first love, "unforgettable".
I can still remember perfectly.
There was a pair of pants, a shirt, a vest type "Gillette" and a jacket from the autumn / winter "collection" 1971 "1972.
"It was a gift from him," says Naty Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him to everyone else because of his great love for women and because he emphasizes our beauty," adds the former Duchess of Feria.
I like the colors he uses very much; they have a lot of light and underline the face.
The proportions are perfect.
Also the princess and opinion leader of the fashion Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg cannot forget the first time when she wore a Valentino.
When I lived in Italy as a teenager, I dreamed of finally having the age and the opportunity to wear one of his evening gowns...
At the end of the nineties it finally came to that.
I bought my first Valentino for a party in the castle of my cousin, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red dress with a flying skirt and a draped top with a décolleté that lives up to its name.
"It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino does not depend on fashion, his obsession is timeless," explains this Italian aristocrat, who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
The princess D'Arenberg keeps her evening dresses of the fashion designer "with absolute care", "because a dress is not only a dress, but also the associated memories".
The "King" of Fashion
