"He was flawless; time leaves no trace on him".
And this says a princess...
The most difficult profession in the world: the human workhorses of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend to the bottom of its crater every day, where the sulphurous gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders along the steep paths made of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted porters need more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle speed, keeping their balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulphur they extract.
Arrived at the top, they make their way between the tourists, whom they photograph like circus monkeys and walk with the tiring heavy baskets three kilometers to the scales, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which since 1960 has been exploiting the deposits in the volcano and (never better said) its workers, paying them 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulphur.
They then sell it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used to produce matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally runs three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wages of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day in the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I took her to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the poisonous gases.
For the past three years, the 27-year-old Anto has risked his life at the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left its first traces on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the poisonous gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I will be working here for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
This likeable and intelligent, but punished by life, young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a stretcher.
It shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur also emanates at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
Approximately 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur onto their shoulders at the bottom of the crater.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining in order to save costs and does not supply any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid for by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 Rupees (2.5 Euros) supplement per camera that the guardians of this Natural Park, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 Rupees (1.2 Euros), charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carriages.
"This work is for animals and not for humans," protests Madrusin, a sturdy, 42-year-old porter who has been working at the Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will carry on "as long as he can", because he needs the money for the education of his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano has been my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, if the wind turns suddenly and the miners get trapped in the thick pillars that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that nobody complains about serious illnesses... of course except the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks on a goat trail between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide with some teeth missing.
Of his five children, the oldest, aged 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but misery continues generation after generation in one of the hardest professions in the world: that of those who work as human donkeys at the Kawah Ijen.
