"The population of Singapore must grow."
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife: let us fulfil our civic duty and let us create life!
It seems unbelievable that the verses are part of an advertisement for mint candy, but nevertheless - or precisely because of this - they became a viral video on YouTube at the beginning of this year in Singapore.
The phrases are part of a rapper ’ s song that features local sayings such as “Push a bao ” (loaf) into the stove to make fun of the low birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising company BBH, which shot the video, preserves the hope that the commercial reaches in a funny way to draw attention to the problem.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says that he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do their "national duty".
This is something for the internet only, so we had to make it fun and funny.
This is the biggest problem in that country.
When it comes to reproduction, we are the worst in the world, so we realized that this is an issue that we had to deal with.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed dancing evenings (quick flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought: why not do something as creative as possible to tackle this problem, such as composing a rap?
1,2 children
Those who do not take this issue lightly are the Singapore government.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its rulers ’ conservatism and strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was over 2 - also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don ’ t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Agency, says that this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities."
“This has enabled people to get married and form a family, and to have many more options in terms of life goals and priorities, ” she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of single people and to the delay of marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration in order to counteract the reduction of the population has led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the little-concealed xenophobia flourishes against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore ’ s ruling party achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and contributions for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the well-known impact on a nation ’ s economic growth, tax revenues, health-care costs, and immigration policies, Singapore ’ s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It is already having an impact on the housing market.
The Department of Urban Development has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoeboxes" that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single and that they discourage the construction companies from building large dwellings for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general director of real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoeboxes" sell much faster than larger residential units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out days and even weeks faster than the larger residential units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards give developers clearer orientations that were previously hampered when they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, talks with Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will have little impact.
"People are very stressed, apartments and education are expensive, which is why many postpone it," says a young manager.
The children can get others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and cost of ownership and education as reasons for not having children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the final say when it comes to having children - the government can do so much about that.
The offline private offline is private online
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What is private for someone under 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he exposes himself if he publishes situations on the Internet that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequently online.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very distinct" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when applying it to social networks.
"I wouldn't reveal my deepest secrets in a post," says 10-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the meaning of "private" in websites such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures of games.
I also spend my time with friends.
"I wouldn't share a photo that isn't of me, or of someone doing the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, of nudes, of crimes, or to write insulting or violent comments.
Jorge assured to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and post interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I just upload them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly with relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
Asked, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone recommended a stranger to him, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask he admits not to know 20 of the people he added to his friends list.
"That doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one gave him any hints or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If someone harasses me or requests it from me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
Experiences known today as cyberbullying are not unknown to the boy.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed in a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he said.
According to José, the victim has not closed his account.
"He only did it privately."
He then explains a number of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do that if he was unpleasant to me or if I wanted to wipe one out of him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to guide children and young people, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a medium for searching for information, but with the appearance of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, holder of a Master ’ s degree in Pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work “Digital Natives and Immigrants ”, used these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are they, the children and young people who have grown up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them, when we are still learning," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue "because we require them to have a defined criterion for what may be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age when maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective when it is most important for them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is, is to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions some possibilities: There are things you would not tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the internet?
Or: Would you like to have a photo of yourself published, like the one you published about a friend?
Do you know what the others publish about you?
Did you ask other people for permission beforehand if you tagged photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Do everyone need to know what you are doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they must act online, as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
“Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks, ” he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational adviser, commented that it is indispensable that parents read the guidelines of social networks carefully.
When they understand all the sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, the age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You shall not talk to strangers".
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was announced beforehand and was to be signed theoretically by the seven leaders present.
Efe repeatedly sought access to the signed document at the Sixth Ordinary Session of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the enclosure, but then stated that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian Government website.
On questions about the text, they indicated that the content was set out by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, in the press room, only the picture of the presidential meeting without sound was broadcast with the message "private session, limited audio".
The little information circulating among the journalists was obtained from the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press secretary.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "Final Declaration" of the Summit, which was the Humala Declaration and not the official document concluding the Summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit between South America and the Arab States (ASPA), and yet again, despite strong press demands, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was not published.
On the official ASPA website, you can see for yourself that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were in place for journalists, but that they severely restricted access to information.
The Summit also concluded with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Court of Justice of The Hague settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins on Monday in The Hague, to listen to the pleas of both sides in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago.
"We will follow and execute the judgement on the differences that we are currently bringing before this international court", said Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," adds Piñera, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious error, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
Present at the summit were the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 following the removal of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host, President Ollanta Humala, opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions had been made and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total investment of 17 billion dollars had been defined.
Commenting on the decisions taken, he said that the countries of Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are extending the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in cities and organised transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not be allowed to take on triumphant features, but should serve to increase our output and show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving the spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas... thus uniting our countries and opening up new forms of economy", said the Peruvian president in a read out statement.
Among these projects, five are Peruvian, located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its readmission to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect emphasised at the summit.
In this sense, before beginning his participation in the regional meeting, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said that he expected a meeting in Mexico on Saturday with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in order to treat the maritime conflict with respect, following a judgment of the ICJ challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe I'll meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these avenues - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary", he underlined.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they intend to attend the inauguration of the country ’ s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the Summit, the Defence Ministers of the bloc also met ahead of the Summit to adopt the 2013 Action Plan to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru holds the presidency for the period of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from the integration of its citizens", says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, confirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America can indeed learn something from Europe."
Correa, who took part in the 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which took place in Lima, told the state television in Peru that the Europeans "perished in the Second World War and in other conflicts" and "are now practically a fatherland."
In this sense, he defended the project to create a South American citizenship, which will advance the member states of Unasur.
"Free movement of citizens and workers must be achieved in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to return to the past," he warned.
The President of Ecuador also advocated the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OEA) with a view to reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those who signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit themselves to anything, and in return we the South Americans always sign everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and funded by the United States," he said, alluding to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to the founder of WikiLeaks, Julian Assange.
Correa asserted that he did not regret this decision, because he had not betrayed his principles, but had complied with his "deep democratic values and views on human rights."
He added that there were "reasonable suspicions at the time that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his case would not be followed."
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary for requiring him to be interrogated on his territory for an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish case-law allows for this by means of a videoconference that could have been carried out through the Ecuadorian Embassy in London."
Correa said that there was a risk that Assange's health and mental condition would be compromised.
"Since he has been in our embassy, I have not spoken to him, but the Ambassador has informed me that he has a slight problem with his lungs, but not a serious one," said the Head of State of Ecuador.
There was, however, a danger that he would suffer physical and psychological damage because he was trapped in a confined space and could not do any physical exercises outdoors.
"That would affect everyone's health," he added.
Correa said that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London since June was to grant him a free pass to travel to Ecuador, and that this was in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European judicial authorities. He underlined that there had been talks with London to find a solution for the imprisoned founder of WikiLeaks.
We are not dealing with human rights, we are not using that word in this case, but there have been constant talks.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European judicial authorities, because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is conducting a series of proceedings at various European levels," he said.
And "if Britain grants this carte blanche tomorrow, I think it will be done."
And if Sweden interrogated Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish law allows and has been done in other cases, the problem is over.
Correa took the opportunity to affirm himself as a defender of press freedom, saying that what he did not tolerate was "the mediocrity, the evil intention and the lie that invalidate freedom of expression."
"The biggest enemies of press freedom are not the wicked and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek profit and blackmail," he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself on the fact that Ecuador is no longer dominated by such journalists "nor by bankers or hegemonic and petty-bourgeois countries," and anticipated that if re-elected, he "will deepen the revolution in order to continue the path in this right direction."
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay in Unasur at least until his next election, arguing that the organism "must be tough and not allow any opportunism and a coup d'etat disguised as legal" because it "destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
The President of Ecuador also considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime borders between the two countries "absolutely legitimate" now and after the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua.
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They must be dealt with comprehensively so that they can be overcome and forward-looking.
He also relied on a good conclusion to the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same court, stating that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international bodies if both countries undertake to accept the judgment, even if it is very harsh."
With regard to the possibility of running as a candidate for the next presidential elections in Ecuador to achieve his third consecutive mandate, he stated that he sees this possibility "with much optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the elections in February 2013, he would withdraw from political life.
Power has never interested me personally, but in such unfair circumstances as in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that it was I who guaranteed this likely victory, so I must shoulder that responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last term as President, after which I withdraw from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he said.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken to the Vice-President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he had gone there for planned, routine treatment and that it was expected that he would be able to return to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not in any case mean a relapse in the state of health of President Chávez," he commented.
