The cause of death from AIDS today is too late recognition
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed as HIV positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says of the moment when he received the diagnosis, which the doctor tried to "weaken" without apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to learn about it, with such commitment that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency “virus ” (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At the time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to an impasse."
At the time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is also possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, there are still many people who come to the clinic who are unaware of their illness and who have already been damaged by the virus and have exhausted their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the appearance of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient receiving treatment on time is exactly the same as the survival of the general population," said HCG HIV unit head Jaime Andrade Villanueva, stating that this information was supported by a respected scientific publication in April this year.
The specialist in infectious diseases and HIV / AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008 scientists have concluded that while AIDS is not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of the individuals at the beginning of treatment, and that those who are not addicted to drugs have greater chances: up to 30 years at a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years at a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above means that those who receive a positive diagnosis of HIV at the age of 25 can "easily live to 75 as long as they are under control", the skilled person explained.
To understand this progress properly, it is important to remember that Mexicans today have an average life expectancy of 76 years.
Even if mortality has declined significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA annual report)), it is nonetheless true that, since the appearance of AIDS, 60% of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by the month of May this year, there had been 187 deaths, although it is claimed that since 2005 there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs.
- So why do people still die from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least for the past 12 years, we have not had any problems with medication, and the problem is that people come in a very advanced state because they do not know their infection status, that is, in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence the global mortality rate, earlier diagnoses are required, which is why all persons who require this must be offered massive detection tests."
This proposal is supported by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) and also by patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test done in a private laboratory, for the sole reason that it was done by a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had Kaposi ’ s sarcoma (a cancerous tumour), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think that they will die and do not want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was towards improvement, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
"I work, I do a lot, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and that of the other person", explains Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO, in order to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today within the framework of the worldwide AIDS day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The earlier they know whether they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like everyone else.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big gaps between the health programmes and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the places designated for this, "the distribution of condoms has actually been increased; previously they were handed over individually, now they give us packages of a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Young people are among the people at risk for new infections.
"What do you need them for?" is a common mockery of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health care system, to whom young people do not want to expose themselves, the correspondent assured.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; the condoms should not only be behind the counter, but in dispensing devices in public toilets of facilities frequently visited by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They should not be paid the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied when asked if condoms would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who already engage in sexual activity," he summed it up.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
Nationally, the state is ranked fourth in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV cases.
92% of infections occur through sexual intercourse, 6% through the blood and 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that there are 50,000 people living with HIV, because for each registered case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
Since the Court of Appeal of the United States has upheld a judgment that does not recognise the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group, which was achieved through a commercial exchange rate in Mexico, a disastrous precedent is being set for any national company with branches in the neighbouring country that has payment problems.
It could be said, therefore, that the procedures for the survival of the companies that allow Mexican laws do not apply in the land of the stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition on 15 June of Judge Harlin Hale ’ s judgment at the Northern District Court in Bancarrotas in Texas has left Mexican companies helpless in the face of confiscation of their property across the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door for the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to refer three inconsistencies to the United States Supreme Court.
While the judge of the case points out that the creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy laws of the United States, the Court of Appeal of the Fifth Circuit, based in New Orleans, initially states that the main proceedings are the trade discourse dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of companies with a transnational profile is not known.
Indeed, to this end, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created, with the American Law Institute as the arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment stipulates that, without the votes of the companies, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been obtained after recognition of the liabilities of the assets held by the branches of Vitro with its parent company.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case where this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities among the group ’ s companies have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles.
It is also true that, after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who brought actions against Vitro before the courts of the United States, i.e. the vultures, funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for his difficult situation since 2008 in the context of the great economic crisis in the United States, which hit the country.
That is why the González Sada family appeals to the same Court of Appeal, so that the vote takes place in plenary, that is, of all the judges, because only three of them voted.
Failure to do so will result in an appeal by the Cerciorare, which requires a higher court to review the case, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
What is serious about this case is that the Court has set aside a document sent by the Mexican Government under the Figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court), which describes the procedure carried out by Vitro under the Commercial Conduct Act and points out that it had adhered strictly to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the Bankruptcy Code of the United States.
It also points out that the country is subject to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee equality between debtors and creditors.
Two-band carambola: a hit for Vitro and for the country.
