Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The globetrotter of basketball, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been associated with basketball for more than 60 years and has travelled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large intellectual collection of the history of basketball in the country as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a player of lower classes, player of the first national league, representative and manager in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the basketball federation.
"All my life I put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the association in the 90s," Reyes remembered during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and bear witness to them.
Bayamón in the Heart
The most emotional memories are those of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-managing director of the club.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most, because I could be part of eight championships of the Vaqueros since 1967 as a managing director, co-managing director or coach.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy debuted at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good administrator, "says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who worked as a coach here and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a very strong player, 2 metres tall.
Do you want him? "
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free-throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who became naturalized and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would provide another.
The championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse was granted to him, but already from a distance, because he was already in the top position of the federation in 1988.
At this time he preferred to enjoy his executions and that of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we won the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico against the USA for the first time.
Then came the World Cup in 1990, where we took fourth place, which should have been bronze, if it hadn ’ t been for this Canadian referee who made us repeat the last move for the second time, said Reyes.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you have ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as the one who won at the Olympics in 2004 against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the team from the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered a fight to the US team, as they did when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
In this team were not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 because of a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great pleasure, was that of the pre-Olympic tournament in 1995 in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the banned players due to the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against every forecast.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as much as Piculín.
And this without considering his career in the various leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
This is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the boys, I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best thing you have achieved?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which at the beginning of the 1990s included up to 17 teams in a single season.
What do you still have to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, only play in their area and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today the children make unnecessary many trips and games.
At least I see the result of prescribed training and courses for coaches, table, officials and referees.
I am proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like listening to music, watching videos of music from my time on YouTube, enjoying my grandchildren and occasionally going to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who has always been at my side.
